    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying for my physics final and im kinda stuck on quantum entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? i dont need the heavy math right now just a conceptual explanation",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a fascinating concept where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are.  If you measure a property of one entangled particle—say, its spin—you instantly know the corresponding property of the other particle.  The difference from classical correlation is that this connection isn't due to any pre-existing, hidden instructions, which is what you might expect from, say, two matching pairs of socks. It's a genuine, spooky connection, as Einstein famously called it.",
